<TEXT>
square 571 is the name given by the 
government to a 43000squarefoot federal building that sits vacant 
in the middle of the district of columbia footsteps away from a 
homeless shelter which lately has been turning away 50 to 75 people 
a night 
a law passed in mid1987 directed the federal government to make 
its underutilized property available to the homeless but square 
571 was beyond the grasp of homeless advocates 
the reason the federal government interpreted underutilized 
to mean partially occupied not vacant 
under that reading of the law only 12 of the us governments 
properties uncle sam owns 429959 buildings and 727 million acres 
of land were deemed suitable for the homeless 
of those two a post office in lynn mass and an office 
building in bell calif have actually been devoted to that 
purpose since passage of the mckinney homeless assistance act in 
july 1987 
these facts outrage homeless advocates who have sued the 
government to force it to make more of its underused and unused 
properties available 
on sept 30 us district judge oliver gasch ruled in the 
advocates favor noting its unreasonable to suggest that 
congress chose to lease to the homeless halfempty properties and 
properties which are used part of the time but no properties which 
are wholly unoccupied 
pitifully few of the numerous unused federal properties are 
being evaluated for their suitability to assist the homeless 
gasch wrote in the decision those that are found to be suitable 
are not being made available to homeless providers 
gasch forbade the federal government from selling or transferring 
any of its excess or surplus properties until it has complied with 
the law 
currently the government has 335 excess or surplus properties 
ranging from a threestory federal office building in downtown 
providence ri to a vacant school in phoenix 
excess property is defined as that which isnt needed by the 
government agency which controls it while surplus property isnt 
needed by any federal agency at all according to earl jones 
commissioner of the general services administrations property 
resources service normally when a piece of federal property is 
declared excess it is turned in to the gsa which can offer it to 
other federal agencies or state or local governments or sell it on 
the open market jones said 
two months after gaschs ruling no more federal properties had 
been leased to the homeless and the parties to the lawsuit went back 
to court the national coalition for the homeless asked for a 
timetable for the government to comply charging that the department 
of housing and urban development was trying to stall 
gasch has given the government until wednesday to review half its 
335 surplus and excess properties to determine suitability for the 
homeless and until jan 12 to assess the other half if it doesnt 
finish on time gasch could find the government in contempt 
asked what the government had been doing in the two months since 
the judges initial ruling james stimson the assistant on homeless 
policy to the secretary of hud said officials were reviewing the 
list and revising the criteria for deciding which properties would 
be suitable for the homeless 
thereve been no major changes he said some additional 
factors were added recently 
those factors were to allow for exclusions of properties in flood 
plains or near hazardous or toxic waste sites or near explosive 
materials he said 
i find that an example of exercise in the absurd spending two 
months to make that change said maria foscarinis attorney for 
the national coalition for the homeless they wasted over two 
months as far as i can tell 
foscarinis said she believed the government was looking for ways 
to exclude more of the properties on the list and was only prevented 
from coming up with more loopholes because they were subjected to 
very close scrutiny by a congressional committee and by us 
stimson denied the allegation 
stimson said hud had identified three properties on the list of 
335 suitable for the homeless and two unsuitable gsa had 
recommended that hud look at those particular properties because 
they might fit the bill stimson admitted 
those that were deemed suitable were the john fogarty federal 
building in providence which is partially occupied a federal 
building in smithfield nc which is fully occupied by the 
department of agriculture and about five acres of land known as the 
raritan depot in new jersey 
those that were excluded a group of buildings at fort hayes in 
columbus ohio because they are structurally unsound and a former 
missile testing site in dade fla because its in a flood plain 
those recommendations have been sent back to the gsa stimson 
said 
</TEXT>
