<TEXT>
soviet economic openness toward the west 
is only budding but it already has produced some flowers even 
though theyre plastic 
the first parcel of plastic flowers and kitchenware from the 
southern soviet city of tashkent reached this port city a couple of 
weeks ago palpable proof that joint ventures with soviet companies 
are not necessarily mired in delays and red tape 
there are already dividends after only one year said frans 
moens of the antwerp plastic merchandising co 
moens holding a bouquet of red plastic roses said antwerp 
plastic controls one of europes oldest producers of plastic flowers 
italys alma rose spa which was approached last year by the 
soviets 
alma rose had long wanted to be a trailblazer with the soviets 
since the early 1970s it offered its services but always met a 
nyet leonid brezhnevstyle said moens referring to the 
former soviet leader 
but things moved quickly with the emergence of mikhail s 
gorbachev and his program for economic reform 
talks started in march 1987 and six months later the 40 million 
joint venture sovplastital was founded a soviet state company holds 
78 percent of the shares with the remainder held by alma rose on 
the board of directors however parity reigns 
key to doing successful business with the soviets said moens 
was setting up an allencompassing business plan the soviets 
rigorously stick to the plan but absolutely everything has to be in 
it he said he compared this with the more practical approach of 
european businesses 
for tashkent the soviets wanted machines materials and the 
knowhow to refine the plastic products while gaining an export 
market to earn them foreign currency 
antwerp plastic and alma rose gained a new production unit 
where wages are still low and a market of 280 million potential 
customers the market is simply enormous and still has to be 
claimed said moens 
an antwerp plastic official who demanded anonymity also said 
alma rose wanted to reduce production in italy because of the many 
labor strikes that is not the case in the soviet union 
the factory in tashkent employs 800 workers and plans to add 300 
soon moens said 
