<TEXT>
prime minister noboru takeshita is expected to 
announce a cabinet reshuffle this week after months of bitter 
parliamentary battles over controversial tax reform and a 
stockprofiteering scandal 
an annual reshuffle of cabinet posts is a firmly established 
custom in japan said seizaburo sato a political science 
professor at tokyo university only 20 portfolios are available he 
said and prime ministers are expected to rotate senior parliament 
members through key posts at regular intervals 
takeshita has said he would announce changes in his cabinet 
sometime this month he is expected to do so soon after parliament 
ends its current extraordinary session tuesday 
press reports quoting unidentified sources said takeshita 
probably would retain those in top cabinet posts such as foreign 
minister sousuke uno and shintaro abe secretarygeneral of the 
governing liberal democratic party 
mr takeshita doesnt want to upset the status quo hell keep 
most important figures but there is a very strong push for some 
change sato said 
takeshitas administration has been under fire for the 
involvement of top party leaders in the recruit cosmos stock 
scandal in which influential figures profited from sales of stock 
bought at bargain prices before the shares were publicly listed 
takeshitas name is among those linked to the scandal 
opposition parties demanding a thorough inquiry into the scandal 
held up debate on tax reform until finance minister kiichi miyazawa 
resigned to take responsibility for an aides involvement in the 
stock deals which were legal although the ethics involved were 
questioned 
even then the path was rough for japans first tax overhaul 
since 1949 
public and political opposition already had delayed tax reform 
for a decade and takeshita made it a top priority when he assumed 
office in november 1987 opposition footdragging left him with the 
choice of abandoning the bills or forcing them through 
on saturday the liberal democratic party used its commanding 
parliamentary majority to enact a tax package that introduces a 3 
percent sales tax and cuts corporate and upperbracket income taxes 
immediately after the bills were passed takeshita named one of 
the architects of the tax reform tatsuo murayama as his new 
finance minister takeshita himself had been acting finance minister 
since dec 9 when miyazawa resigned 
approval ratings for the takeshita administration have plummeted 
over its handling of the stock scandal and tax package takeshitas 
tax victory was greeted with a chorus of criticism from the local 
press 
the pattern of the ruling party steamrolling its bills and 
stalling tactics by the opposition have been repeated so often 
that it goes to show just how sick japanese politics have 
become said the national newspaper asahi shimbun 
in an unusually vehement editorial the englishlanguage japan 
times said the whole process leading up to passage of the tax 
bill has illustrated in a disgusting way how arrogant the 
government party has become how deeply tainted by money the 
nations politics is how unprincipled many politicians and some 
political parties are 
the liberal democratic party said tax reform was needed to 
eliminate inequities in the tax burdens of salaried wage earners and 
the selfemployed opposition critics maintain however that the 
tax bill will do little to eliminate unfairness or close tax 
loopholes 
in addition to establishing the sales tax takeshitas tax 
package slashes duties on imported liquor and automobiles reduces 
the basic corporate tax rate from 42 percent to 375 percent and 
cuts the maximum income tax rate from 60 percent to 50 percent 
the most affected will again be pensioners and those in 
lowerincome brackets and salaried consumers who will have to 
pay more for food and other daily necessities covered by the new 
tax the japan times said 
