<TEXT>
the soviet union launched its first national 
multicandidate election campaign monday with 100 communist party 
members and ordinary citizens entering the race 
mondays nominees including a retired army general and economic 
reformer have exactly three months to win the suddenly unguaranteed 
votes of their comrades their campaigns may include free television 
time and an unpaid staff of 10 volunteers 
a government reform law november dropped decades of 
singlecandidate balloting for communist party nominees in favor of 
unlimited candidates for 2250 seats in the new congress of peoples 
deputies nominating will continue for another month and balloting 
is set for march 26 
even the official soviet news agency tass admitted monday that 
soviet elections were largely reduced to a formality in the past 
voters had no choice of candidates and nominees were chosen 
according to social status age and sex to guarantee filling quotas 
for factory workers and other demographic groups tass said 
in the time of soviet dictator josef stalin people who 
registered objections by vainly voting no risked a 25year 
prison term 
under president mikhail s gorbachevs reorganization precinct 
caucuses workers grouped by company or industry and certain public 
organizations ranging from the communist party to the academy of 
sciences may nominate an unlimited number of candidates 
congress will meet once a year and elect a nearly fulltime 
parliament from among its members 
the soviet union first experimented with multiple candidates in 
some local council elections june 1987 they resulted in the 
communist party losing its majority control in some councils to 
nonparty members 
nevertheless the party is guaranteed preeminence by the 
soviet constitution which also prohibits other political parties 
the one visible opposition group the democratic union spends much 
of its time agitating for the right to exist 
in moscow signs popped up monday identifying precinct meeting 
sites 
public interest was less than overwhelming however according to 
soviet media although work groups must have 500 members to nominate 
a candidate the vote in one minsk computer factory was just 368 a 
local communist party official overwhelmed her opponent a shift 
supervisor known for her honorable character and painstaking work 
mondays tass report answered one serious objection to 
gorbachevs reform plan the possibility a person could be elected 
to fill more than one congressional seat since twothirds of 
representatives will be chosen by territorial district and onethird 
from organizations it was possible a person could be nominated in 
his region and also by several organizations 
but tass said an election commission would register the nominees 
at the end of the first month of the campaign to prevent one person 
running in several districts simultaneously tass did not say if the 
commission would have the power to bar candidates for other reasons 
