<TEXT>
mexico may no longer be a major exporter of 
oil by the end of the century unless new crude deposits are found 
because domestic consumption continues to rise the mexican 
petroleum institute said monday 
the institute said in a report the state petroleum monopoly pemex 
will have to cut down on exports and increase current proven 
reserves by at least 125 billion barrels during the next 11 years 
just to keep up with growing domestic demand 
mexicos total energy consumption is currently equivalent to 
2325 million barrels of crude oil daily 80 percent of which is 
made up of petroleum and the rest is generated by hydroelectric 
plants according to the report 
this could go up to the equivalent of 37 million barrels daily 
by the year 2000 and to 59 million barrels by the year 2010 the 
institute said 
the countrys proven oil reserves currently stand at about 72 
billion barrels of crude it produces 25 million barrels daily and 
sells 1325 million barrrels mostly to the united states making it 
the worlds sixth largest exporter 
</TEXT>
